{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502507"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:45:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:45:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1868"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1868"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.09,0.11,0.08,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1868"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106935"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1868"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1868"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89421"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"3670"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"609"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27545"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39125"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43857"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106935"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for follow-up two weeks after completing treatment for \u003Cem\u003EClostridioides difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection. She initially developed diarrhoea following amoxicillin treatment for a chest infection. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She completed a 10-day course of vancomycin and her symptoms have completely resolved. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender with normal bowel sounds.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No further follow-up required","Repeat stool toxin testing","Prophylactic vancomycin","Repeat stool PCR testing","Faecal microbiota transplantation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has had complete resolution of symptoms following treatment for \u003Cem\u003EClostridioides difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection. \u003Cstrong\u003ENo further follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E is required as she has responded to therapy with complete resolution of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat stool toxin testing\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended in asymptomatic patients who have responded to treatment. Up to 50% of successfully treated patients may continue to have spores in their stool for up to 6 weeks after treatment completion, making test results difficult to interpret and not clinically useful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProphylactic vancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in patients who have had a single episode of C. difficile infection that has resolved with treatment. Prophylaxis may be considered in select cases of recurrent infection requiring ongoing antibiotics for other conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat stool PCR testing\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended in asymptomatic patients who have responded to treatment. PCR testing is even more likely than toxin testing to remain positive after successful treatment as it detects the presence of \u003Cem\u003EC. difficile\u003C/em\u003E DNA regardless of whether the organism is viable or producing toxin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFaecal microbiota transplantation\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for patients with recurrent \u003Cem\u003EC. difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection who have failed standard antibiotic therapy. It is not indicated for patients who have responded to initial treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Asymptomatic patients who have responded to treatment for Clostridioides difficile do not require follow-up stool testing.","Up to 50% of successfully treated patients may continue to have C. difficile spores in their stool for 6 weeks after treatment."],"references":["Guery B, Galperine T, Barbut F. Clostridioides difficile: diagnosis and treatments. BMJ 2019; 366:14609"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89421"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1868"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89421"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-24T09:57:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-24T09:57:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1868"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106935"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group"